<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the Chair of the Crime Statistics Advisory Committee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">[CST0007]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I am replying on behalf of the National Statistician’s Crime Statistics Advisory Committee (CSAC) for England and Wales of which I am the Chair. It was established as an independent advisory committee on crime statistics following a recommendation from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2010 National Statistician's Review of Crime Statistics. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC functions as a strategic, high level advisory body offering independent advice to the Home Secretary, the Office for National Statistics (ONS) and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HMIC) on matters related to the measurement of crime and the collection and presentation of crime data for England and Wales. It advises on how best to ensure that official statistics on crime are accurate, clearly presented, comprehensive, transparent and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> trustworthy taking account of the needs of users and providers. Annex 1 provides further information about the Committee.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:-0.05pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the focus of this inquiry, your Select Committee may be interested to know what CSAC has been doing on this front. It has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considering issues arising from the apparent divergence of trends between the Crime Survey for England and Wales (CSEW) and Police Recorded Crime (PRC). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC welcomed and supported the publication of the report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by ONS on this topic which provided new inf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ormation suggesting that the PRC series has been falling at a faster rate than suggested by the independent CSEW. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is is important information which will help users interpret trends in crime. CSAC plans to receive further evidence on this issue in the com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing months. CSAC has also supported and provided guidance to HMIC on their planned Inspection Programme of Crime Data Integrity.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC believes that there is a strong public interest in the crime data recorded by the police being accurate, clearly presente</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d, comprehensive, transparent, and trustworthy. The police service themselves need accurate data to enable forces to understand and respond to crime problems in their area. If crimes go unrecorded, or mis-recorded, then the risk is that the police will not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> properly understand trends in criminality which will hinder their response to it. Police and Crime Commissioners also require reliable data if they are to properly hold Chief Constables to account. Those providing services to victims require accurate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reliable data to enable them to plan services and support bids for funding. The public rely on such data to inform them about the risk of crime in their local area.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The system of crime recording in England and Wales compares well with other jurisdictions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The National Crime Recording Standard (NCRS) requires forces to adopt a victim-focused approach to crime recording such that victims’ reports of crime should be recorded unless there is credible evidence to suggest that no crime occurred. This provides a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">good framework for a consistent approach to crime recording across the police forces of England and Wales. Few other jurisdictions have such a systematic approach to recording crime and those that do have generally modelled their systems on the system used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in England and Wales. However, there is scope for improvement and CSAC has made some suggestions in response to the specific questions that the inquiry seeks to address. Answers to those questions can be found in Annex 2.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Crime Statistics Advisory Committee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Origins of the Committee</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Crime Statistics Advisory Committee has its origins in the National Statistician’s Review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of Crime Statistics in England and Wales</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the report of whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ch was published on 6 June 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> following the Home Secretary’s acceptance of its recommendations. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key findings were that:</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the presentation of crime statistics need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further improvement to provide clarity about the coverage of the two sources of crime statistics – the Crime Survey </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and police recorded crime – and to maximise the benefits of complementary sources to provide a fuller picture of crime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there should be transparent decision-making on changes that affect the published crime statistics;</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the National Statistician should establish an independent Advisory Committee to advise: </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) the Home Secretary on any changes to the data requirements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the police needed for crime statistics, and on any changes to the Home Office Counting Rules; and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ii</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) the producer body on changes to coverage, definitions or methodology and on the handling of any such changes; and,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(iii) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Office for National St</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">atistics (ONS) should assume responsibility for the independent reporting and publication of crime statistics.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report also contained a recommendation that quality assurance of police recording of crime should be re-focused by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Constabulary (HMIC) on risk areas in terms of the statistical quality of the data.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Membership of the Committee</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Committee is comprised of a majority of ‘non-executive’ members representing academia, users and the like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">officials from government dep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">artments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> representatives from key stakeholder organisations. Members are subject to a Code of Practice. The Chair of the Committee is Professor Stephen Shute, who was appointed to that role in December 2011 following an open competition. The other non-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">executive members were also appointed through open competition. For more details on membership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">please refer to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Committee’s webpage</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Functions and Scope</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Committee functions as a strategic, high level advisory body offering independent advice to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Home Secretary, the Office for National Statistics (ONS) and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary (HMIC) on matters related to the measurement of crime and the collection and presentation of crime data for England and Wales. It advises on how best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to ensure that official statistics on crime for England and Wales are accurate, clearly presented, comprehensive, transparent and trustworthy taking account of the needs of users and providers. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In carrying out its functions the Committee has due regard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to:</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the needs of users and providers of data; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Code of Practice for Official Statistics; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the wider affordability of proposals for change; burden or bureaucracy in respect of Police Recorded Crime and on the public who provide survey data; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.31pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ational developments and obligations.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Committee’s Terms of Reference were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Dece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mber 2011 and include commitments to :</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Advise on changes in the coverage, definitions, classifications or methodologies</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">underpinning crime statistics, both for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Crime Survey for England and Wales</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or other crime surveys and police recorded crime including keeping a watching</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brief on the Crime Survey for England and Wales to see how it can be developed</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further. This includes the handling of any changes;</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the crime categories used for collection and publication of police</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:21.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recorded crime;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consider how non-notifiable offences might be reflected in published statistics, with a view to reducing burden on the police and improving presentation in statistical rel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eases; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Advise the Home Secretary on the statistical implications of any changes, additions or deletions to the Home Office Counting Rules (HOCR) and the National Crime Recording Standard (NCRS); </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and,</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Receive reports from HMIC on their audit programme of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> police crime recording and data integrity and advise it on the statistical and quality requirements for police recorded crime including the identification of areas for further review.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q1. Are crimes being recorded by the police when they should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e? Are crimes being categorised correctly?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should be recognised that crime recording is a complex business. There are in the region of 1,400 different criminal offences covered by the Notifiable Offence List; that is those offences that the police must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report to the Home Office for inclusion in the crime statistics. There is extensive guidance in the Home Office Counting Rules (HOCR) setting out the correct recording of them into the 126 categories that appear in the official statistics on crime. There a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re 43 individual territorial police forces in England and Wales and the British Transport Police with thousands of police officers and staff involved in the crime recording process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ONS work, cited above, suggests that there has never been a time when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 100% of crimes reported by victims to the police have been recorded on their systems. There may be good reason why this is so, such as the crime as reported falling outside the scope of the notifiable offence. However, it would appear from the ONS analysi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that the introduction of the NCRS in April 2002 was instrumental in driving up the proportion of crimes recorded. The ONS evidence also suggests that there seems to have been a degree of rolling back of compliance with the NCRS in recent years which, if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">substantiated, has the potential to undermine the value and trustworthiness of police recorded crime.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q2. What are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If there is evidence that not all crimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are being recorded accurately, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will want to understand the reasons why. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is aware of anecdotal evidence including high profile media cases that suggests target-driven culture may be part of the explanation. The recent HMIC inspection in Kent, prompted by concerns by the Police and Cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ime Commissioner about crime recording practise, “found that a target-driven culture had, until recently, led to some officers in Kent pursuing crimes on the basis of how easy they were to solve, rather than on their seriousness, or their impact on victims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or communities” and that HMIC considered “these activities were motivated by the desire to meet monthly performance management targets in relation to the number of disposals (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ibid. crimes cleared up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) attained.” If this finding is replicated in other force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that is a cause for concern. C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> hopes that the position will become clearer once HMIC has conducted its forthcoming national inspection. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to note that other factors may also have a bearing. For example, C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has heard concerns from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Association of Chief Police Officers (ACPO) that officers view the current crime recording system as overly bureaucratic and so rigid that it impairs the use of professional discretion. It is not clear the extent to which these concerns relate to the NCRS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> itself or to the way in which individual force systems have established additional bureaucracy around the crime recording process. C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wishes to explore further the potential to make reductions in unnecessary bureaucracy around crime recording while bein</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g mindful of the need to assess the possible impact on crime statistics and public trust in them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considers that there is scope to streamline the crime recording process, without damaging the statistics, by forces reviewing their own internal proces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ses.  For example, at our last meeting, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">endorsed the issuing of best practice guidelines in respect of the recording of Additional Verifiable Information (AVI).Under the HOCR, AVI is required before a crime report can be struck off the books, for exampl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e in the case of a false report of a crime having taken place. It seems that some forces were taking a risk-averse approach to AVI such that they were requiring officers to provide the same level of detail for a trivial matter (e.g. a member of the public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">phoning to say that the property they thought had been stolen had been found) as for a serious allegation (e.g. a victim withdrawing an allegation of serious sexual assault). If police officers perceive the crime recording process to be burdensome then the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re is a risk that they may decide not to record crimes if the effort in doing so outweighs the perceived benefit.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q3. Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function effectively and accurately? </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is not in a po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sition to respond to this question but it understands that HMIC will be assessing this issue as part of their forthcoming inspections. C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> expects to comment on the results of these inspections and to make recommendations to the Home Office, ONS or HMIC a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bout the implications of the inspections for the collection, presentation or future inspection of the statistics.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q4. Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HOCR encourage forces to undertake periodic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">internal audit to check on the accuracy of the crime recording process within force. However, a thematic inspection by HMIC, published in 2012, reviewing police and crime incident reports found “limited evidence of forces directly assessing whether their o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wn crime quality audits provided confidence that their crime figures gave an accurate account of their performance”. This suggests that more can be done by forces themselves to make use of their internal audits.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believes that it is necessary to suppl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ement an internal audit with regular annual independent inspection by HMIC or similar body. Such inspections need not be costly if they are risk-based and proportionate in scope. C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> believes that such audits will act as an incentive for forces to keep th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eir house in order but more importantly serve the public interest in providing transparent information on the reliability of published recorded crime statistics.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q5. To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he recording of crime by police forces?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All statistical series have their limitations and imperfections. The producers of statistics need to fairly and objectively document them to ensure users are aware when basing decisions on those statistics. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SAC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has been working with ONS to improve the presentation of crime statistics for England and Wales and has offered its support to continue these improvements. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welcomed the analysis that ONS published about trends in the two main series of cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ime. This noted that both series have been consistent in documenting a downward trend in crimes covered by the two series over the last decade. The analysis also suggested that the rate of reduction in the recorded crime series was over-stated, possibly as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a result of an erosion of compliance with the NCRS. This is important information for users of these statistics to be aware of, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> believes such transparency will build confidence in the integrity of official statistics.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics? </span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The designation of official statistics as National Statistics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">matter for the UK Statistics Authority and outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CSAC’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sphere of competence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Courier; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/method-quality/specific/crime-statistics-methodology/methodological-note--analysis-of-variation-in-crime-trends.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/national-statistician/ns-reports--reviews-and-guidance/national-statistician-s-reviews/national-statistician-s-review-of-crime-statistics.html"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">National Statistician’s Review of Crime Statistics for England and Wales: UK Statistics Authority</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/national-statistician/ns-reports--reviews-and-guidance/national-statistician-s-advisory-committees/crime-statistics-advisory-committee-membership.html"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Crime Statistics Advisory Committee Membership: UK Sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">tistics Authority</span></a></p></body></html>